The '''Phelan Building''' is an 11-story office building located at 760 [[Market Street (San Francisco)|Market Street]] in the [[Financial District, San Francisco|Financial District]] of [[San Francisco, California]]. It has a triangular shape reminiscent of the [[Flatiron Building]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], with its tip at the meeting point of [[Market Street (San Francisco)|Market Street]], O’Farrell Street, and Grant Avenue. It is a [[List of San Francisco Designated Landmarks|San Francisco Designated Landmark]].

The building was designed by [[William Curlett]] and built in 1908 by [[James D. Phelan]] on the place of the first, original Phelan Building, damaged by the [[1906 San Francisco earthquake|1906 earthquake]] and fire. It was once home to the George Haas and Sons Candy Store, marketed as the most beautiful candy shop in the country.<ref>https://www.mercurynews.com/2008/02/09/boxes-used-to-come-with-more-than-just-candy/</ref> Their business also operated a tea room on the second floor.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=5qhvCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT142&lpg=PT142&dq=george+haas+phelan&source=bl&ots=Kjb5pHmT0Y&sig=ACfU3U2vJ8Upg5fMdw-wT5AKB-M6DYJu4g&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi8it64--TgAhWKm-AKHWASBfMQ6AEwEXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=george%20haas%20phelan&f=false</ref>

==The original Phelan Building==

The first Phelan Building was constructed in 1881 by James Phelan, the father of James D. Phelan. It was a 6-story, [[bay window|bay-windowed]], [[mansard]]-roofed flatiron.<ref name="phelanbuilding">{{cite web|url=http://www.phelanbuilding.net/building.htm|title=The Phelan Building History|publisher=phelanbuilding.net|accessdate=2014-04-29}}</ref> Despite being advertised as “thoroughly fire and earthquake proof”,<ref>{{Citation|title=Phelan Building advertisement|publisher=Fraternal Record|date=July 24, 1886}}</ref> the building was badly damaged in the 1906 post-earthquake fire, and its ruins were subsequently dynamited on April 20, 1906.<ref name="nps">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/prsf/historyculture/1906-earthquake-fire-fighting.htm|title=1906 Earthquake: Fire Fighting - Presidio of San Francisco  (U.S. National Park Service)|publisher=nps.gov|accessdate=2014-04-29}}</ref>

